stock_scanner.condition.doc: Module for conditions used in stock scanning. To write your own conditions, write a class that inherits from Condition and implements its interface.

stock_scanner.condition.Above150And200SM.doc: Example condition. Checks if a stock's current price is above its 150- and 200-day SMA.

The constructor generally should be concerned with the attributes later used when assessing the truthhfulness of this condition being fulfilled.

Args
  • stock (Stock)
The method that determines whether the condition is fulfilled or not.

stock_scanner.condition.Condition.Condit.doc: Base class all other conditions must inherit from and implement methods for.

Args
  • stock (Stock): An instance of a Stock to check condition for.
The method checks if the condition is met for the supplied stock.

stock_scanner.condition.Consolidating.Co.doc: Base class all other conditions must inherit from and implement methods for.
The method checks if the condition is met for the supplied stock.

stock_scanner.data_fetcher.doc:
Module for fetching the data for stocks later to be used in a scan. If you want to build your own custom data fetcher for a certain API, for instance, you need to write a class that implements the interface defined in DataFetcher.

However, there is the existing class YahooDataFetcher which should be plug-and-play, as it downloads data from Yahoo's open finance API. It's not 100% reliable, but should suffice for use-cases where a few false negatives is acceptable.

stock_scanner.data_fetcher.DataFetcher.D.doc: Base class defining the interface of all data fetchers.

Args
  • universe (str): The name of the universe (one implementation could for example allow "nasdaq" or "sp500")
  • path (str): The path to where the stock data should be downloaded.
Downloading/reading a list of all tickers in the given universe and sets them as self.tickers Note, that it should also return self to allow for method chaining.
A convenient getter method for the ticker list.

Downloading the data for stocks in the given the given universe.

Args
  • start_date (datetime): From when should the data be downloaded (e.g. "let's download data from 2020-06-18")
  • end_date (datetime): Until when should the data be downloaded (e.g. "let's download data from 2020-06-18 to 2021-06-18")
  • verbose (bool, optional): Whether the download should be verbose, for example by displaying progress or which ticker is currently being downloaded. Handy for debugging purposes.

Return the path to the file for a stock.

Args
  • ticker (str): Ticker for a stock (e.g. "AAPL")

stock_scanner.data_fetcher.YahooDataFetc.doc: Base class defining the interface of all data fetchers.

A DataFetcher downloading OHLC data from Yahoo Finance. There are rate limits, but it should realistically not be a problem. It makes use of yahooquery, which also has the capability to download more qualitative data - if you're interested in that for a custom DataFetcher.

It also downloads the stock data in CSV format. If you develop a custom DataFetcher you may use a different format, but remember to use a compatible DataReader in that case.

Args
  • universe (str, ["sp500", "nasdaq", "dow", "ftse100", "ftse250", "nifty50", "niftybank"]): The name of the universe.
  • path (str): The path to where the stock data should be downloaded.
  • verbose (bool, optional): Whether the fetching should be verbose (display progress etc.) or not. Default is False.
Attributes
  • universe (str): universe
  • path (str): path
  • tickers (List[str]): tickers
Downloading/reading a list of all tickers in the given universe and sets them as self.tickers Note, that it returns self to allow for method chaining.
A convenient getter method for the ticker list.

Downloading the data for stocks in the given the given universe.

Args
  • start_date (datetime): From when should the data be downloaded (e.g. "let's download data from 2020-06-18")
  • end_date (datetime): Until when should the data be downloaded (e.g. "let's download data from 2020-06-18 to 2021-06-18")
  • verbose (bool, optional): Whether the download should be verbose, for example by displaying progress or which ticker is currently being downloaded. Handy for debugging purposes.

Return the path to the file for a stock.

Args
  • ticker (str): Ticker for a stock (e.g. "AAPL")

stock_scanner.data_reader.doc:
Module for reading local stock files and returning Stock instances. If you want to build your own custom data reader for a certain file format, you need to write a class that implements the interface defined in DataReader.

However, there is the existing class CSVReader which should be plug-and-play when used in conjunction with the YahooDataFetcher.

stock_scanner.data_reader.CSVReader.CSVR.doc: Class for reading in stock OHLC and volume data from CSV files saved by the YahooDataFetcher.

The constructor is concerned with what delimiter is used in the CSV files, and mapping the CSV column names. All parameters are optional, and the default values work with files saved by YahooDataFetcher.

Args
  • delimiter (str, optional): The delimiter used in the CSV files. Can usually be left at default and automatically detected.
  • close_key (str, optional): Name of the column for the close value.
  • volume_key (str, optional): Name of the column for the volume value.
  • open_key (str, optional): Name of the column for the open value.
  • high_key (str, optional): Name of the column for the high value.
  • low_key (str, optional): Name of the column for the low value.
  • date_key (str, optional): Name of the column for the date value.

Read data from a ticker's file and return Stock.

Args
  • ticker (str): Ticker of the stock.
  • path (str): Path to stock's data file.

stock_scanner.data_reader.DataReader.doc: This module contains the abstract class defining the interface ALL DataReaders need to implement.

stock_scanner.data_reader.DataReader.Dat.doc: No specified interface here. However, DataReader implementations should be be concerned with information such as formatting of the data, value mapping and similar things in the constructor. See CSVReader as an example.

Read data from file and return a Stock instance. A stock ticker (e.g. "AAPL") and directory path should be given, and the file name resolution should be the concern of this method.

Args
  • ticker (str): Ticker of the stock (e.g. "AAPL").
  • path (str): Path to the the ticker's file.

stock_scanner.export.doc:
This is a package for exporting a list of scan candidates to persistent formats.

  1. Save a list of the tickers to a text file (saveTickersToFile)
  2. Save static charts of the stocks in PNG format (saveToPNG)
  3. Save interactive HTML charts of the stocks (saveToInteractive)

stock_scanner.export.SaveTickersToFile.doc: This module defines the function for saving a list of stock tickers to a text file.

stock_scanner.export.SaveTickersToFile.s.doc:
Saves a list of stock candidate tickers to a file.

Attributes
  • attr1 (str): Description of attr1.
  • attr2 (int, optional): Description of attr2.

Parameters path: str Path to directory where the file should be saved file_name: str Name of file to be saved stocks: List[Stock] List of Stocks

stock_scanner.scanner.doc:
Module for scanner classes that are concerned with the overarching logic of performing a scan. If you want to build your own custom scanner, you need to write a class that implements the interface defined in Scanner.

For rapid development of a basic scanner, on the other hand, BasicScanner should be an ready-to-use class for many use-cases.

stock_scanner.scanner.BasicScanner.Basic.doc: Basic scanner class which should be sufficient for many use cases. You may want to write your own version for more advanced scans.

Args
  • conditions (List[Condition]): List of conditions stocks returned from scan should fulfill.
  • data_fetcher (DataFetcher, optional): An instance of DataFetcher, default is YahooDataFetcher.
  • data_reader (DataReader, optional): An instance of DataReader, the default is CSVReader and is compatible with files saved by YahooDataFetcher.
  • validator (Validator, optional): An instance of Validator, the default is BasicValidator.

Loads all stock data required for the scan.

Args
  • period (int, optional): How many days back you want data for each stock. The default is 365, so in that case you fetch daily data from today to a year back.
  • verbose (bool, optional): Whether the download should be verbose, i.e. show progress or what stock is currently being downloaded.

Return candidate stocks from the scan.

Args
  • verbose (bool, optional): Whether the process should be verbose, IE show progress or what stock is currently being analyzed.

stock_scanner.validator.Validator.Valida.doc: Abstract Validator class What is a Validator? It essentially takes a stock, looks at the given conditions, and decides whether the stock should be returned as a scan candidate or not.

The implementation of your validation should be made here. ...
